segments.text: Well, I don't know what you call him, an alcoholic or not.
He got drunk a lot, at least what I consider.
So he had to be relieved, in other words.
Yeah, he was moved out.
Now, you say that you had bombers and fighters, a warning system.
What was the size of each one of these wings that you...
How many bombers did you have?
How many fighters?
How many men did you have?
Well, the 38th Bomb Group was a B-26 outfit.
It was located at Tama, Japan and it also had a 25th Type Recco squadron and oh I'd probably estimate that it had maybe about 30 B-26's and oh say 400 officers and men.
Eighth Fighter Group over at the Shia was a P-51 outfit and it had three squadrons of P-51s and probably 15 airplanes each squadron.
And the 347th Fighter Interceptor Group was F-61s and they were located at Izuku and that was just a squadron.
And then your Air Command and
And the warning group was scattered at various radar sites throughout the area, and I would say maybe 100 people at each one.
All together, I would say probably about 5,000 people.
5,000 people that you commanded?
I would say 5,000, maybe not that much.
Or I would say around 2,500 maybe.
Oh, okay, 2,500.
Yeah.
All right.
And what was your aim?
What was the aim?
Well, what were you there for?
You were in the war.
Obviously, occupation, you didn't have to keep the Japanese people down, according to your description of them.
Why were you there?
What was your mission?
Well, to occupy Japan, actually.
And you had your air command and warning group set up so that any aircraft from Russia or China, you would intercept.
But most of it was the control of airplanes over Japan.
I mean, you owned airplanes.
They were Japan's air defense though.
Air defense, yeah.
They were completely cut out.
You had, see we had two 315's and then you had the 314's.
One of them had the northern part of Japan and the other one had the southern part of Japan.
And those were the two air defense systems in Japan?
Yeah, and they were composite wings.
Then you had a troop carrier group and troop carrier outfits and then you had an air
Materiel Command.
That consisted of the 5th Air Force.
Okay.
Now, during this period you had a shift from friendship with the Soviet Union, 1944-1945, to unfriendly relations, enemies with the Soviet Union.
by about 1947, 1948.
You also have the Chinese Civil War in which the Communists won.
Did you, what was the impact of this rising Cold War on the military in Japan?
Well, other than being more alert, I don't think it had any impact.
You weren't increased in size.
Every once in a while you had an alert of an unidentified object.
And sometimes you never knew what it was.
And other times you decided it was a weather phenomenon that you were able to look over a mountain range and see moving boats or ships or something of this sort.
But I don't...
I think the biggest problem we had then was just training and getting the combat organizations that we had up to combat status.
After all the pilots, all the experienced pilots and all the military experienced enlistment, we went home getting back into flying again.
Okay, so your basic function then was to
keep these units prepared in the case.
Yeah.
Okay, did you, on the island of Japan, did you have nuclear capabilities?
Did you have American atomic bombs?
I don't think so.
No, I don't question it at that time.
They were all, I'm sure, they were kept back on Guam.
And we didn't have any airplanes that were
capable of carrying a nuclear bomb.
There's no reason to take atomic bombs into Japan.
So back on Guam the B-52s or the B-29s at that time and a little bit later the B-36s and then?
Those were the ones that were, our nuclear defense then was on the island of Guam and you never had those large bombers in Japan.
Why didn't you have those large bombers in Japan?
Well there's no place to put them really.
You didn't have an airport large enough?
Well the airfields that Japanese built just weren't built for those big airplanes.
And I don't think that, I don't think we ever had any
B-29 stationed in Japan.

Now we had one or two that passed through there that landed at, we built an airport at Tachikawa and they had some record that they flew one of them back to the states and that they were trying to establish, which they did establish a record, a long range record.
but they just weren't stationed there.
So we had B-25s, A-26s, B-26s and P-51s and that type of airplane.
This is your first overseas assignment except for the time that you went to England and that really wasn't a permanent assignment.
What were your impressions of being in the Air Force overseas?
It really didn't make any difference where we were.
I went in the 11th of September of 45 and then moved into Johnson and then Lois and the two girls joined me in August of 46.
And they brought an old automobile over, brought a 1940 Buick over.

and we drove it all over Japan and it was really pretty nice when I was commanded 350 there division why I had a railroad car that I could have the Japanese hook on the rear of any train go anywhere in Japan.
Really?
Oh yeah, oh yeah.
And we had opportunity to visit the many of the
hot springs of Japan, the big hotels that the military had taken over as arrest hotels.
And we had, well when I arrived in Japan, a Japanese assigned to me a Japanese soldier as my valet.
Oh yeah.
Could he translate also?
Well, he couldn't translate.
He could speak a little English, but he learned English.
Then when Lois and the girls arrived over there, we were assigned two more girls, a housekeeper and a housemaid.
In fact, you could get as many servants as you could fit.
Oh really?
Oh yeah.
And the Japanese government paid for it.
Yeah, we had a cook who was a cook on one of the big luxury liners that was owned on one of the Japanese luxury liners before the war.
So his food was good.
His food was good.
He was really good.
And he just cooked for you or for other families?
Oh, he just cooked for us.
Oh, wow.
And so we had
One house boy, one cook, and two house maids.
I mean, a housekeeper and a nurse maid, whatever you call them.
Did junior grade officers also get servants?
Well, they may not have gotten as many.
They got as many as they wanted to feed, actually.
The Japanese were anxious to get more people out of the hungry line.
Mm-hmm.
I see, yeah.
So this Japanese boy, before it all started, he washed all your clothes, and cleaned and pressed your trousers, cleaned your room, made your bed, and took care of you in general.
He stayed with us the whole time.
Now did you live on the base or did you live off the base?
Well in Johnson, when I was in the 5th Bomber Command, I lived on base.
We had a Quonset hut that you built yourself.
This lady said here's some Quonset huts.
If you want to build a house for you and your family, have at it and they give you an area where you can build it.
So you got yourself some Japanese workers and you built yourself a house.
And of course they were real good at ceramic tile and this type of thing.
And then opening down at Nagare where we lived in a great big Japanese mansion off base.
And then down in Izuzuki we lived on base.
But down there you had a, by that time you had housing that was built to American specifications on base.
And you had commanders going on the quarters that was built.
But no, that tour was real.
real nice really.
And you visited most all of the hot spots.
The Army took over most of the golf courses and of course we went looking one day, when we were down at Izuki, we went looking for
a Methodist orphan's home, and we ended up in a Catholic orphan's home that the French nuns were running, and the French nuns couldn't go home.
All the U.S. nuns were evacuated, but the French, once they leave France, why they stayed in Japan.
Now we had a little
So they couldn't go home during the war.
They couldn't go home during the war at all.
So they were still there and they were in bad, bad shape.
You mean as far as supplies?
Yeah, food, supplies.
They'd be able to raise money and because Japan was real poor and we would take them a lot of food that we'd collect and kind of adopted them as
And it was real interesting.
It made you feel good.
I betcha.
So you had a good tour then in Japan.
Oh yeah, that was a real good tour.
And you could buy things real cheap.
You buy big plates that are a couple of dollars a piece.
Probably worth two or three or four hundred dollars the second time we went over there.
Then you came back to the States.
Let's move back here.
Command of the United States Air Force Security Service 1949 to 1951.
Tell me about that.
Well see when I came back from Japan I went to the Air War College at Maxwell and I spent a year there.
Oh that's right.
And that was, I think we had about 100 Air Force officers, Air Force, Navy, and Marine, and Army officers going through there.
And it was... What was that instituted?
Was that first instituted about that time?
Oh, I would say I was about the third class, or third or fourth class.
And it was
Well it was kind of an executive development type of program.
I would think so.
Probably a fairly elite assignment wasn't it?
Yeah, in fact only about 2% of the officers in the Air Force ever get to attend it.
Oh really?
Well how can you account for the fact that you got to attend it?
Well I don't know, I guess I had a good record.
And did you apply for it?
No, but I was
Where I just happened to hit it probably at the right time.
I was coming back from overseas and had a good time to go to school.
What kind of classes did they have?
Can you compare it to the way they ran West Plain?
No, this was a pure and simple, an executive type of relaxing thing.
You had seminars that you did a lot of talking back and forth on and you played golf.
and your wives had courses in how to be a good Air Force wife.
Really?
Oh yeah.
What did they tell her?
Well, you had to support your husband in his career and Air Force etiquette.
and all this type of thing.

I mean it's more of a course of supporting the officers wives club, the NCO wives club and the airmen wives club and all this stuff and the social services that you, special services that you get into, family services.
for new families coming on base, this type of thing.
I wonder if in this day of woman's liberation they'd still have a course like that for the wives at the Aramore College.
I don't know.
I think they are because I think our daughter is involved in a briefing as to what their responsibilities are and their learning program is while her husband's at this school.
Now tell me tell me what uh what type of classes you had?
Well a lot of it was uh was uh strategy uh type of thing another one was communications how to how to communicate uh up and down within an organization a lot of management type of uh

top management type of programs, human relations, responsibilities between the Air Force and the civilian community, how to keep that and joining the Chamber of Commerce and your various clubs that you have.
and have a volunteer speaker's toastmaster type of organization on base so you can go out and tell them what the Air Force is doing.
This type of thing.
Community relations?
Community relations type of thing.
How about courses on leadership?
Yeah, well you had, I can't remember specifically about any, but all of this, on human relations, senior media, personnel management,
type of thing.
And you had real outstanding lecturers.
You had people like the president of General Motors or top executives in the industry would come down and talk to you about
about personnel programs or executive programs or what it takes to be a leader type of thing.
A lot of it was just a talk program.
Communication, the ability to communicate with others?
Yes.
Did they give you grades?
No.
Did they have assignments?
Yeah, they have assignments.

Well during each phase you would have an outline of reading that you had to do and like Eisenhower White House, it may not have been at that particular, that's either National War College or there, but there was a long article in either Fortune or I think it was in Fortune which had on Eisenhower's White House.
organize the White House, and how you use the staff, and things of this sort.
What about courses on politics?
How to get along with politicians for future generals, anything like that?
Oh, I think you probably have a lot of that.
Some of it, I don't remember exactly.
I'm sure I have a curriculum out in my file, but I don't exactly remember.
How large was each class?

Or you had about 10 or 15 in each class and then you stayed with them maybe two weeks and during that two weeks you had a seminar party at somebody's house where everybody brought either dessert or meat or vegetables or what have you.
So you got to know everybody in your seminar real well.
How many total students were at the War College?
Well, I think it was about a hundred at the time.
And it was a one-year course?
Well, yeah, she graduated 27th of June and you started out the latter part of August.
I see.
Do you think, overall now, thinking back on and thinking of your career, was it worthwhile
Did you actually learn things about it?
Well, I would say you think at the time that had you attended the War College before you were commander of the 315th, that you could have run the 315th Air Division a lot better.
I see.
Because it gave you a lot better insight on how to handle people.
Yeah, sure.
management, things that you're going to be doing.
Yeah.
Okay, let's shift now then to the commander of the United States Air Force Security Service.
Can you tell me about that?
Well, when I graduated from the Air War College, I really volunteered to go to Washington to be in personnel.
I figured that there was a lot to be desired in personnel
I figured that during my whole career, I don't think I got my first choice or even second choice as to what I wanted to do or where I wanted to be.
And I figured that at least we should be able to hit it 50% of the time.
But because I hadn't had any personnel experience, I got assigned to the Air Force Security Service.
Well, the Air Force Security Service was just being organized at the time.
And I didn't, when I inquired around when I got my orders as to what the airport security service was all about, why no one in the class knew anything about it.
So I flew down to Brooks Field here in San Antonio to make a survey.
Well, it was such a super secret organization why they wouldn't even let me in.
Really?
It was so secret that they wouldn't let you in, and you were destined to become the commander?
Well, the thing about it, they didn't know that at that time.
They hadn't seen any orders or anything.
And you're supposed to have a clearance.
You're supposed to have a background in investigation.
And you didn't have a top secret security clearance?
I'd been involved in a lot of top secret office, but at that time they didn't know my status and therefore they wouldn't let me in.
So I came down and took command, well they had a Colonel Lynn who was a commander then and I took command about four days after I got here and he was transferred up to Washington.
and it was a small outfit and then that was again a building program of establishing intercept stations worldwide.
Intercept for what?
Intercom in error?
Intercept stations of anything that's
radio, on the radio, on radio, you intercepted and tried to read everybody else's mail.
Right.
So, and Why do you think this was established, Air Force Security Service?
Well, when we, see we had, where you have the, right at the time, you had the Army,
and the Navy had an organization such as this, and when we separated, then the Army gave up some experienced people, and so the Air Force formed a security service.
So each organization has its own intercept, and it's quite important when you're up
close to the enemy lines to be able to intercept any direction that you have on guns, on their artillery, or anything of that sort.
So it's basically that type of organization.
Did you have any relations with the CIA, which was established in 1947?
I mean, it sounds like you're doing some of the same things that they're doing.
Well, the CIA, we put a lot of information in the CIA, and also the Army and the Navy.
And yeah, I had a lot of, as Commander of the Security Service, I was on the National Security Intelligence Committee.
and which the director of CIA, I believe, was the chairman of that type of thing.
It was really pretty well coordinated.
There was a lot of jealousy between
the CIA and its ability to produce intelligence vis-a-vis the military intelligence field.
Oh, really?
Well, it's always been that way.
A lot of rivalry?
A lot of rivalry.
Which one does a better job, the military or the CIA?
They're really different fields, actually.
Could you explain?
No, I don't know.
I don't think I can.
Well, the civilians and the military intelligence and the civilians and CIA are big competitors of production of intelligence.
and who's right and who's wrong when they produce a piece of intelligence.
But that was a very interesting command.
Again, you were building and that was my specialty and I moved from there up to
Deputy Director, National Security Agency.
So, you have two jobs right in a row from 1949 to 1951, then from 1951 to 1953 that deals with intelligence and security.
Yeah.
Well, see, I was in communications.
Sure.
That's why you were chosen, because you were in communications.
Is that what you think?
Yeah, well, most of all of the
what you did there was intercept radio signals.

And that was, and the National Security, well that deputy director was a job of which I was pretty well bored at, because you really, it was a staff job of which you was responsible for keeping the Air Force informed as to what was going on in the National Security Agency.
and wanted to be sure that they got all of the intelligence that was produced.
But you really didn't have any command responsibility.
And you'd been a commander before, so this is...
So I got quite bored there, and that's when I, it was during this time that I got my master's degree in business administration.
Okay, we're going to talk about that in a minute.
Let's talk about the relations that you had with the CIA and the National Security Agency.
How did you work with those people?
Well, we provided them with all our products, and then of course they, I presume,
you know, had all the other sort of, numerous other sources of intelligence, and they, their responsibility was to tie them all together, to be sure that the stuff that their agents picked up by...
